#: ../../user/troubleshooting/resume-suspend-troubleshooting.rst:143
#: 65bc1224f47749c08530c26ce6e9a0c4
msgid "Power consumption increases on suspend/resume"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/troubleshooting/resume-suspend-troubleshooting.rst:146
#: 61a945a1176d47a18ecd6eb2150919b9
msgid ""
"This problem is related to the software method used to disable sibling "
"threads and how it interacts with suspend/resume. To solve the problem, "
"disable hyper-threading in the BIOS. This `external guide "
"<https://www.pcmag.com/news/how-to-disable-hyperthreading>`__ explains "
"how to disable hyper-threading. Since Qubes does disable hyperthreading "
"by default (by not using secondary threads), you won’t pay any "
"performance cost."
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/troubleshooting/resume-suspend-troubleshooting.rst:149
#: 055b456b73c74073ac5c5f37747fb549
msgid "Attached devices in Windows HVM stop working on suspend/resume"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/troubleshooting/resume-suspend-troubleshooting.rst:152
#: fa0b4ff795914204bcab9b20cff94875
msgid ""
"After the whole system gets suspended into S3 sleep and subsequently "
"resumed, some attached devices may stop working. To make the devices "
"work, they should be restarted within the VM. This can be achieved under "
"a Windows HVM by opening the Device Manager, selecting the actual device "
"(such as a USB controller), ‘Disabling’ the device, and then ‘Enabling’ "
"the device again. This is illustrated on the screenshot below:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/troubleshooting/resume-suspend-troubleshooting.rst:154
#: 6d49c67929ae4b8f9b61d61026c97e8e
msgid "r2b1-win7-usb-disable.png"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/troubleshooting/resume-suspend-troubleshooting.rst:160
#: 94bb665374554995af411be877386e74
msgid "Suspend turns off the screen and gets stuck"
msgstr ""

#: ../../user/troubleshooting/resume-suspend-troubleshooting.rst:163
#: c03e5c1e5ab84c27a99ae6386511bd20
msgid ""
"On some devices suspend-to-RAM does not work and a hard power-off is "
"needed to recover, because the system does not go into deep sleep. To get"
" suspend to work, you need to add ``mem_sleep_default=deep`` kernel "
"option. For legacy boot, or UEFI/legacy in R4.1+, add it to the "
"``GRUB_CMDLINE_LINUX`` setting in ``/etc/default/grub``, update the grub "
"config, and reboot. In R4.0 with UEFI boot, you need to add it to every "
"``kernel=`` line in ``/boot/efi/EFI/qubes/xen.cfg`` and reboot."
msgstr ""

